objects.name: Create Concept (Information)
objects.description: From the Palette (left pane) drag the **Information** and drop it into the Container **Types**. Give the object a **name**. Right-Click the object to edit description and **proposedType**. The attribute "proposedType" is used to give the Concept-/ Information-object a proposed TypeName. The TypeName will replace the Typename of this object. ![image001](images/help/Edit-ProposedType-2023-10-05.png) Click on the picture to open in New Tab!

objects.name: Create Relationship between Concepts
objects.description:
Connect two EntityType objects. 

  -Point the cursor to the edge of the object (a curved arrow appears). Click and hold while dragging over and drop on an other object. Select Relationship type **relationshipType**.

  -Then edit the relationship name to give it a name.

objects.name: Create Tasks working on the Information
objects.description: From the Palette (left pane) drag **Role** Type and drop it into the "Task container". Give the task a name (should contain a verb) and description. Drag the relationship **worksOn** from **Task** to **EntityType.** ![image001](images/help/-2023-10-05.png) Click on the picture to open in New Tab!

objects.name: Create performing Roles
objects.description:
From the Palette (left pane) drag **Role** Type and drop it into the "Role/Task container". Give the task a name and description.

(Role here is more a "process role" than an "organisational role"
Its normally not a Position)
 

Drag the relationship **worksOn** from **Task** to **EntityType.**

<details><summary>More about Role</summary>

(from ChatGPT)

In general, an organizational role refers to a specific position or job within an organization, while a process role refers to a specific role or responsibility within a business process.

An organizational role is typically defined by the organization's structure and hierarchy, and is often associated with specific responsibilities, authority, and accountability. Examples of organizational roles include manager, director, and team lead.

A process role, on the other hand, is typically defined by the specific business process being executed, and is often associated with specific tasks, activities, and decision-making responsibilities. Examples of process roles include approver, reviewer, and executor.

In summary, while both organizational roles and process roles are important in defining the structure and responsibilities within an organization, they differ in terms of their scope and focus.
</details>

subModels.name: Metamodelling Tasks
subModels.description:
To build the new Metamodel we have to define the **ObjectTypes** and **RelationshipsTypes** we want to use.
This is done by building a **Type-definition-model_TD** based on the **AKM-CORE_MM** metamodel.

objects.name: Build a Type-definition model ...
objects.description:
## Build Type Definition Models (TD) To build the new Metamodel we have to define the **ObjectTypes** and **RelationshipsTypes** we want to use. This is done by building a **Type-definition-model_TD** based on the **AKM-CORE_MM** metamodel.
Create Initial Containers ... Let us start with an empty model and the built-in ***AKM-Core_MM*** metamodel: ![Initial page with blank modelling area and AKM-Core_MM types in the Palette](/images/posts/modelling/image_model001.png) The left pane contains the object types in the initial metamodel, that the user can use to build a type definition model. From the Palette (left pane) drag the ***Container*** type and drop it into the Modelling area. Click on the name and edit ***name*** ( Name it ***"Domain Types"*** i.e. ***"Bikerental Types"***). Right-Click the object to edit ***description***. ![Create EntityType](images/help/Create-EntityType.png) Click on the picture to open in New Tab!
---
Create EntityTypes ... From the Palette (left pane) drag the ***EntityType*** and drop it into the Container ***"Domain" Types***. Click on the name and edit ***name***. Right-Click the object to edit ***description*** and ***proposedType***. The attribute "proposedType" is used to give the Concept-/ Information-object a proposed TypeName. ![Create EntityType](images/help/Create-EntityType.png) Click on the picture to open in New Tab!
---
Create Relationship types ... 1. 1 - Click on the edge of an Object and drag the cursor to another object. ![image001](images/help/Add-Property-2023-10-05.png) Click on the picture to open in New Tab...
1. 2 - Click on the name of the Relationship to edit.
1. 3 - Right-Click on the relationship to open the properties panel, where you can edit Name, description etc.
---
Add Properties ... From the Palette (left pane) drag the ***Property*** type and drop it into the Container ***"Domain" Types***. Click on the name and edit ***name***. Right-Click the object to edit ***description***. ![Create EntityType](images/help/Add-Property.png) Click on the picture to open in New Tab!
---
Add Values ... From the Palette (left pane) drag the ***Value*** type and drop it into the Container ***"Domain" Types***. Click on the name and edit ***name***. Right-Click the object to edit ***description***. ![Create EntityType](images/help/Add-Value.png) Click on the picture to open in New Tab!
---
Add Fieldtype ... From the Palette (left pane) drag the ***Fieldtype*** type and drop it into the Container ***"Domain" Types***. Click on the name and edit ***name***. Right-Click the object to edit ***description***. ![Create EntityType](images/help/Add-Fieldtype.png) Click on the picture to open in New Tab!
---
Add InputPattern ... From the Palette (left pane) drag the ***InputPattern*** type and drop it into the Container ***"Domain" Types***. Click on the name and edit ***name***. Right-Click the object to edit ***description***. ![Create EntityType](images/help/Add-InputPattern.png) Click on the picture to open in New Tab!
---
Add ViewFormat ... From the Palette (left pane) drag the ***ViewFormat*** type and drop it into the Container ***"Domain" Types***. Click on the name and edit ***name***. Right-Click the object to edit ***description***. ![Create EntityType](images/help/Add-ViewFormat.png) Click on the picture to open in New Tab!
---
Add Metamodel Object ... From the Palette (left pane) drag the ***Metamodel*** type and drop outside the Container ***"Domain" Types***. Click on the name and edit ***name***. Right-Click the object to edit ***description***. Drag a relationship with type ***contains*** from til ***Metamodel*** object to the EntityType objects to be included in the new Metamodel. ![Create EntityType](images/help/Add-Metamodel.png) Click on the picture to open in New Tab!

objects.name: Modify the Type-definition Model --
objects.description: If something is wrong, or you want to change anything, go back to the type definition model, do the necessary changes, and generate the metamodel again. If you want to add symbols and colors to your types, go back to your type definition model to add view specifications, and generate the metamodel again. The view specifications are done by editing *Object View* of the *EntityType* objects and by editing *Relationship View* of the *relationshipType* relationships. The *Object View* and *Relationship View* definitions are used to define the corresponding *Object Typeview* and *Relationship Typeview* definitions in the generated metamodel. ![Create EntityType](images/help/Add-Metamodel.png) Click on the picture to open in New Tab!

objects.name: Generate a new Metamodel ...
objects.description:
### Generate the new Metamodel
 
The first time you want to generate a metamodel from the type definition model, there are a few things you need to do:

Generate the metamodel content by right clicking the background and choose ***Generate Metamodel***. Follow the dialog questions:

- ***Do you want to exclude system types***? Click *Ok*.
- ***Select Target Metamodel***. Confirm the metamodel in the list.  

You should then get the message: ***Target metamodel has been successfully generated!***.

Now it is time to verify your metamodel, to see if you are able to build the desired model based on the type definitions you just created.
(see next step)

objects.name: Build a Use-case Model
objects.description:
We build our model by first dragging and dropping first "*Person*" and then "*Car*". We click on each of them to edit their names:

![alt text](/images/posts/modelling/image_model004.png)

Then when we draw a relationship between the two objects, we are asked to choose a relationship type: 

![alt text](/images/posts/modelling/image_model005.png)

We choose ***owns*** in the modal dialog that pops up, clicks on ***Done*** and the relationship is created. (If you click on the *x* in the top right corner of the dialog, the operation is canceled.)

We continue modeling objects and relationships and may end up with a model like this:

![alt text](/images/posts/modelling/image_model006.png)


### Modifying object and relationship views

How objects and relationships is visualized in the model (icon, fillcolor, framecolor, etc.) is defined in the typeview definitions for each the type. The appearance can be overridden by defining objectviews and relationshipviews.


The objectview of the person *Me* looks like this:

![alt text](/images/posts/modelling/image_model007.png)

We see that we can modify the fillcolor of the object, the *strokecolor*, the *icon* as so on, and then give the object a specialized look that differs from the default appearance. 

We can do the same with relationships, and modify the color, the arrowheads, and so on, when we want to deviate from the default.

objects.name: More documentation ...
objects.description:
##### Naming conventions for Models and Metamodels ###### Models -Concept models: modelname_CM -Type-Definitions: modelname_TD -Solution models: modelname_SM ##### Metamodels -metamodelname_MM
### Type-Definitions_TD Model To make a new Metamodel, we need to define the Object- and Relationship types we want to be in the Metamodel. In order to create these types, we use the EntityType and RelshipType from the ##### AKM-CORE_MM Metamodel ![image001](images/posts/CustomMeta/Picture1.png) More info : How to make Custom Metamodels...

objects.name: Example model ...
objects.description:
### The example

In this chapter we will use an example metamodel as defined below. It has four different object types, "*Person*", "*House*", "*Apartment*" and "*Car*", with relationship types "*owns*" and "*rents*" as shown in the next model diagram.

There are four *EntityType* objects, each representing an object type in the intended new metamodel. Their names are the planned object type names.
There are six *isRelatedTo* relationships, each representing a relationship type in the new metamodel. Each *isRelatedTo* relationship is renamed to its planned relationship type names. These are the names you see in the diagram.

![alt text](/images/posts/modelling/image_model031.png)

This small type definition model is enough to generate a new metamodel, that will allow you to model people, houses, apartments and cars, and link them together with the appropriate relationships.

objecttypes.name: Value
objecttypes.description: Value represents the specific data assigned to a Property. It defines the actual content or figure, such as a numerical amount, text string, or boolean state, that the property holds.

objecttypes.name: ViewFormat
objecttypes.description: ViewFormat typically refers to a setting or attribute in software that determines how data or information is displayed or formatted in a user interface. It controls the visual presentation of data, such as layout, style, or format, enhancing readability and user experience.

objecttypes.name: InputPattern
objecttypes.description: InputPattern typically refers to a predefined format or rule that an input must follow. It's used to validate or guide user input, ensuring it matches a specific structure, like a date format or a phone number pattern. RegEx is typically used to specify the pattern.

objecttypes.name: Fieldtype
objecttypes.description: FieldType typically specify of the type of data contained in a field. (text, textarea, select, checkbox, radio, date, time, color)

objecttypes.name: Datatype
objecttypes.description: A datatype is a classification identifying the type of data, such as integer, string, or boolean, which determines the possible values for that type, the operations that can be performed on it, and the way it is stored.

objecttypes.name: Property
objecttypes.description: A property is an object representing an attribute of an entity that holds basic data, such as strings, numbers, or booleans. It defines specific characteristics of the entity, like 'name' or 'age'.

objecttypes.name: RelshipType
objecttypes.description: RelationshipType Object is used as a placeholder for relationship Properties. It will be generated as a relationship with  attributes.

objecttypes.name: EntityType
objecttypes.description: An EntityType represents a category or class of similar entities in a data model, For example, a 'Customer' could be an EntityType with relationships to properties like name and address.aaaaaa

objecttypes.name: Metamodel
objecttypes.description: Metamodel is a model that defines the Object and Relationship-types, rules and structures for creating other models. It provides a higher-level framework for understanding how different elements in a model relate and interact.

objecttypes.name: Method
objecttypes.description: Method is a function associated with an EntityType (object or class), defining an action or behavior the object can perform. It often manipulates the object's data properties and can return values.

objecttypes.name: MethodType
objecttypes.description: MethodType typically refers to an attribute that specifies the type or category of a method or function.

objects.name: Build a Type-definition model ...
objects.description:
## Build Type Definition Models (TD) To build the new Metamodel we have to define the **ObjectTypes** and **RelationshipsTypes** we want to use. This is done by building a **Type-definition-model_TD** based on the **AKM-CORE_MM** metamodel.
Create Initial Containers ... Let us start with an empty model and the built-in ***AKM-Core_MM*** metamodel: ![Initial page with blank modelling area and AKM-Core_MM types in the Palette](/images/posts/modelling/image_model001.png) The left pane contains the object types in the initial metamodel, that the user can use to build a type definition model. From the Palette (left pane) drag the ***Container*** type and drop it into the Modelling area. Click on the name and edit ***name*** ( Name it ***"Domain Types"*** i.e. ***"Bikerental Types"***). Right-Click the object to edit ***description***. ![Create EntityType](images/help/Create-EntityType.png) Click on the picture to open in New Tab!
---
Create EntityTypes ... From the Palette (left pane) drag the ***EntityType*** and drop it into the Container ***"Domain" Types***. Click on the name and edit ***name***. Right-Click the object to edit ***description*** and ***proposedType***. The attribute "proposedType" is used to give the Concept-/ Information-object a proposed TypeName. ![Create EntityType](images/help/Create-EntityType.png) Click on the picture to open in New Tab!
---
Create Relationship types ... 1. 1 - Click on the edge of an Object and drag the cursor to another object. ![image001](images/help/Add-Property-2023-10-05.png) Click on the picture to open in New Tab...
1. 2 - Click on the name of the Relationship to edit.
1. 3 - Right-Click on the relationship to open the properties panel, where you can edit Name, description etc.
---
Add Properties ... From the Palette (left pane) drag the ***Property*** type and drop it into the Container ***"Domain" Types***. Click on the name and edit ***name***. Right-Click the object to edit ***description***. ![Create EntityType](images/help/Add-Property.png) Click on the picture to open in New Tab!
---
Add Values ... From the Palette (left pane) drag the ***Value*** type and drop it into the Container ***"Domain" Types***. Click on the name and edit ***name***. Right-Click the object to edit ***description***. ![Create EntityType](images/help/Add-Value.png) Click on the picture to open in New Tab!
---
Add Fieldtype ... From the Palette (left pane) drag the ***Fieldtype*** type and drop it into the Container ***"Domain" Types***. Click on the name and edit ***name***. Right-Click the object to edit ***description***. ![Create EntityType](images/help/Add-Fieldtype.png) Click on the picture to open in New Tab!
---
Add InputPattern ... From the Palette (left pane) drag the ***InputPattern*** type and drop it into the Container ***"Domain" Types***. Click on the name and edit ***name***. Right-Click the object to edit ***description***. ![Create EntityType](images/help/Add-InputPattern.png) Click on the picture to open in New Tab!
---
Add ViewFormat ... From the Palette (left pane) drag the ***ViewFormat*** type and drop it into the Container ***"Domain" Types***. Click on the name and edit ***name***. Right-Click the object to edit ***description***. ![Create EntityType](images/help/Add-ViewFormat.png) Click on the picture to open in New Tab!
---
Add Metamodel Object ... From the Palette (left pane) drag the ***Metamodel*** type and drop outside the Container ***"Domain" Types***. Click on the name and edit ***name***. Right-Click the object to edit ***description***. Drag a relationship with type ***contains*** from til ***Metamodel*** object to the EntityType objects to be included in the new Metamodel. ![Create EntityType](images/help/Add-Metamodel.png) Click on the picture to open in New Tab!

objects.name: Modify the Type-definition Model --
objects.description: If something is wrong, or you want to change anything, go back to the type definition model, do the necessary changes, and generate the metamodel again. If you want to add symbols and colors to your types, go back to your type definition model to add view specifications, and generate the metamodel again. The view specifications are done by editing *Object View* of the *EntityType* objects and by editing *Relationship View* of the *relationshipType* relationships. The *Object View* and *Relationship View* definitions are used to define the corresponding *Object Typeview* and *Relationship Typeview* definitions in the generated metamodel. ![Create EntityType](images/help/Add-Metamodel.png) Click on the picture to open in New Tab!

objects.name: Generate a new Metamodel ...
objects.description:
### Generate the new Metamodel
 
The first time you want to generate a metamodel from the type definition model, there are a few things you need to do:

Generate the metamodel content by right clicking the background and choose ***Generate Metamodel***. Follow the dialog questions:

- ***Do you want to exclude system types***? Click *Ok*.
- ***Select Target Metamodel***. Confirm the metamodel in the list.  

You should then get the message: ***Target metamodel has been successfully generated!***.

Now it is time to verify your metamodel, to see if you are able to build the desired model based on the type definitions you just created.
(see next step)

objects.name: Build a Use-case Model
objects.description:
We build our model by first dragging and dropping first "*Person*" and then "*Car*". We click on each of them to edit their names:

![alt text](/images/posts/modelling/image_model004.png)

Then when we draw a relationship between the two objects, we are asked to choose a relationship type: 

![alt text](/images/posts/modelling/image_model005.png)

We choose ***owns*** in the modal dialog that pops up, clicks on ***Done*** and the relationship is created. (If you click on the *x* in the top right corner of the dialog, the operation is canceled.)

We continue modeling objects and relationships and may end up with a model like this:

![alt text](/images/posts/modelling/image_model006.png)


### Modifying object and relationship views

How objects and relationships is visualized in the model (icon, fillcolor, framecolor, etc.) is defined in the typeview definitions for each the type. The appearance can be overridden by defining objectviews and relationshipviews.


The objectview of the person *Me* looks like this:

![alt text](/images/posts/modelling/image_model007.png)

We see that we can modify the fillcolor of the object, the *strokecolor*, the *icon* as so on, and then give the object a specialized look that differs from the default appearance. 

We can do the same with relationships, and modify the color, the arrowheads, and so on, when we want to deviate from the default.

subModels.name: Build a Concept Model
subModels.description: ### Concept Model (TD) Model As a way to Explore and Understand the problem space. we will create a Product-(Information and Concepts) and Functional-model (Tasks and Roles) ##### Example Model ![image001](images/help/ISPIM-Concept1-2023-10-10.png) Click on the picture to open in New Tab! As you see there are also additional ObjectTypes that can be added to the TD-model here. Vi use the IRTV_MM Types to build this model. ##### IRTV_MM Metamodel ![image001](images/help/IRTV-2023-10-10.png) Click on the picture to open in New Tab! The main Objecttypes in IRTV is Information Role, Task and View EntityTypes. These are the types that will be generated to Object types in the resulting Metamodel. In addition we have the proposedType Property added to the IRTV EntityTypes. The MetaModel Object is used to point to which EntityTypes are included in the metamodel, in this cas IRTV EntityTypes You can find more info following this link : A Demo Solution Model...

objects.name: Create Concept (Information)
objects.description: From the Palette (left pane) drag the **Information** and drop it into the Container **Types**. Give the object a **name**. Right-Click the object to edit description and **proposedType**. The attribute "proposedType" is used to give the Concept-/ Information-object a proposed TypeName. The TypeName will replace the Typename of this object. ![image001](images/help/Edit-ProposedType-2023-10-05.png) Click on the picture to open in New Tab!

objects.name: Create Relationship between Concepts
objects.description:
Connect two EntityType objects. 

  -Point the cursor to the edge of the object (a curved arrow appears). Click and hold while dragging over and drop on an other object. Select Relationship type **relationshipType**.

  -Then edit the relationship name to give it a name.

objects.name: Create Tasks working on the Information
objects.description: From the Palette (left pane) drag **Role** Type and drop it into the "Task container". Give the task a name (should contain a verb) and description. Drag the relationship **worksOn** from **Task** to **EntityType.** ![image001](images/help/-2023-10-05.png) Click on the picture to open in New Tab!

objects.name: Create performing Roles
objects.description:
From the Palette (left pane) drag **Role** Type and drop it into the "Role/Task container". Give the task a name and description.

(Role here is more a "process role" than an "organisational role"
Its normally not a Position)
 

Drag the relationship **worksOn** from **Task** to **EntityType.**

<details><summary>More about Role</summary>

(from ChatGPT)

In general, an organizational role refers to a specific position or job within an organization, while a process role refers to a specific role or responsibility within a business process.

An organizational role is typically defined by the organization's structure and hierarchy, and is often associated with specific responsibilities, authority, and accountability. Examples of organizational roles include manager, director, and team lead.

A process role, on the other hand, is typically defined by the specific business process being executed, and is often associated with specific tasks, activities, and decision-making responsibilities. Examples of process roles include approver, reviewer, and executor.

In summary, while both organizational roles and process roles are important in defining the structure and responsibilities within an organization, they differ in terms of their scope and focus.
</details>

objecttypes.name: Property
objecttypes.description: A property is an object representing an attribute of an entity that holds basic data, such as strings, numbers, or booleans. It defines specific characteristics of the entity, like 'name' or 'age'.

objecttypes.name: EntityType
objecttypes.description: An EntityType represents a category or class of similar entities in a data model, For example, a 'Customer' could be an EntityType with relationships to properties like name and address.aaaaaa
